    "body": "**Describe the bug**\r\nWhen using `split(...)`, Spark uses the default behavior from the JDK's Pattern class. In particular, it handles a zero-width match using the following logic:\r\n\r\n```\r\n When there is a positive-width match at the beginning of the input sequence then an empty leading substring is included at the beginning of the resulting array. A zero-width match at the beginning however never produces such empty leading substring.\r\n```\r\n\r\nHowever, the underlying cuDF does use include a leading empty substring (to be consistent with Python/Pandas) in the output when using split by regular expression. \r\n\r\n\r\n**Steps/Code to reproduce bug**\r\nExample:\r\nFor the input string 31313 and the pattern 4?, split will produce ['3','1','3','1','3'] on CPU, and ['','3','1','3','1','3'] on the GPU.\r\n\r\n**Expected behavior**\r\nThe output should be consistent between the CPU and GPU in this case so we can enable this edge case on the GPU.\r\n",
